/*
Apparently the code up there is a default settings for a basic c_cpp_propertiess.json generated from vscode....
It guesses your operating system and automatically names the configuration "Linux"
It grabs the first default compoler...which apparaently is clang-18????
it sets the include path to look on your current folder ./src <---this one I think....

"compileCommands": [ "${workspaceFolder}/build/compile_commands.json" ]
that json file is a compilation database. When you compile a ROS2 workspace using colcon, you can pass a specific flag that tells the compiler to write down the exact path
of every single library, header and dependency it touches during the build process. By linking that database to VScode,  Intellisense becomes incredibly smart
and auto-completes everything perfectly without you having to manually type out a lot of complex paths where your header files may reside....
to get that argument say....
"colcon build --cmake-args -DCMAKE_EXPORT_COMPILE_COMMANDS=ON"
*/
{
    "configurations": [
        {
            "name": "ROS2 AI Racer",
            "includePath": [
                "${workspaceFolder}/**",
                "/opt/ros/humble/include/**"
            ],
            "defines": [],
            "compilerPath": "/usr/bin/g++",
            "cStandard": "c17",
            "cppStandard": "c++17",
            "intelliSenseMode": "linux-gcc-x64",
            "compileCommands": "/home/ubuntu/ros2_workspaces/build/compile_commands.json"
        }
    ],
    "version": 4
}